The rate of polymerization equation can be modified to include the initiator efficiency (f) as shown in Eq. 7.53. The equation indicates the polymerization rate is proportional to the square root of initiator concentration and to the first power of monomer concentration. Thus, doubling the initiator concentration causes the rate to increase by a factor of about 1.4. This relationship has been confirmed experimentally for a variety of free radical polymerizations. Propagation and termination rate constants, for several commercially important monomers are given in Table 7.10. The tetrafluoroethylene has an extremely low \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
