Kinetic chain length is related to a variety of rate and concentration parameters. It will decrease as both of initiator concentration and initiator efficiency increase. This is reasonable because increasing the number of growing chains increases the probability of termination. Thus, varying initiator concentration can control molecular weight. In the absence of any side reactions, kinetic chain length is related directly to degree of polymerization depending on the mode of termination. If termination occurs exclusively by disproportionation, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \overline{DP} = \overline{\nu } $$\end{document}; if it occurs by coupling, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \overline{DP} = 2\overline{\nu } $$\end{document}.

When a chain transfer agent is used in polymerization, it is necessary to redefine the kinetic chain length as being the ratio of propagation rate to the combined rates of termination and transfer, as7.65\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \overline{\nu }_{tr} = \frac{{R_{p} }}{{R_{i} + R_{tr} }} $$\end{document}

Since transfer reactions are second order, with7.66\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
